veins of her calf with no proximal extension. The patient does not take any medications apart from the oral contraceptive pill, commenced six weeks ago. The patient is advised to immediately cease the oral contraceptive pill.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate management option?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Unfractionated heparin for six weeks","Direct-acting oral anticoagulant (DOAC) for six weeks","Direct-acting oral anticoagulant (DOAC) for six months","Unfractionated heparin for three months","Direct-acting oral anticoagulant (DOAC) indefinitely"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDeep-vein-thrombosis (DVT) is a blood clot that forms commonly in the lower extremities but has the potential to dislodge and cause an embolus in the lungs. The formation of these clots is encouraged by Virchow\u2019s triad which involves:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDamaged endothelium\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReduced blood flow\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHypercoagulability\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe use of exogenous hormones such as the oral contraceptive pill increases hypercoagulabilty and increases the risk clot formation. The fundamental treatment of this condition involves anticoagulation and improvement of blood flow. Blood flow can be improved with the skeletal activity of the lower legs during walking and compression stocking that gently squeezes the leg. Anticoagulation involves the use of a direct-acting oral anticoagulant (DOAC), low molecular weight heparin or fondaparinux. The duration of this therapy revolves whether the clot formation was provoked (by a specific cause, within three months) or unprovoked.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProvoked DVT and first-time unprovoked distal DVT both have a low risk of recurrence. Distal DVT which is caused by a transient provoking factor (such as pregnancy, esotrogen-containing therapy, leg injury with decreased mobility for more than three days) is treated with minimum six weeks of anticoagulation. An unprovoked distal DVT or proximal DVT warrants a minimum of three months of anticoagulation. The therapy can be extended to six months, however studies have shown that the risk of recurrence did not increase after just three months of therapy. Indefinite duration of anticoagulation is recommended for patients at a constant high risk of recurrence such as in the case of underlying malignancy or a second unprovoked DVT. Where there is a provoked DVT and the risk factor persists, then a three month period of anticoagulation with a DOAC is recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe current thinking is that the oral contraceptive pill is a provoking factor if commenced within three months of the DVT, but not automatically considered the same if it is used for more than three months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case a \u003Cstrong\u003Esix week course of a DOAC\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate. An oral anticoagulant will be better tolerated by the patient that one that must be given by subcutaneous injection (heparin).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA thrombosis screen should never be performed in the setting of a provoked episode unless the severity or thrombotic burden seems out of proportion to the provoking event. For example, if a patient post cardiac surgery was in ICU for several days, immobilised, and had a saddle pulmonary embolus (PE), that would be proportional to the multiple provoking factors (immobilisation, major surgery). Whilst a saddle PE for a patient who simply started the OCP a few weeks ago or underwent day surgery without prolonged immobilisation would raise suspicion for an underlying cause, then a thrombophilia panel would be reasonable. However, in this case, there is no clinical evidence of a PE and clot is confined to the deep veins of her calf, so a thrombosis screen is not necessary.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A six week course of a DOAC is the recommended treatment for a provoked distal DVT."],"references":["Kearon C, Akl E. Duration of anticoagulant therapy for deep vein thrombosis and pulmonary embolism. Blood [Internet]. 2014Mar20 [cited 2020Apr30]; Available from:\u00a0https://ashpublications.org/blood/article/123/12/1794/32733/Duration-of-anticoagulant-therapy-for-deep-vein","Waheed S, Kudaravalli P, Hotwagner D. Deep Vein Thrombosis (DVT). StatPearls [Internet]. 2020Jan29 [cited 2020Apr29]; Available from:\u00a0https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507708/","Tran HA et al. New guidelines from the Thrombosis and Haemostasis Society of Australia and New Zealand for the diagnosis and management of venous thromboembolism. The Medical journal of Australia 210(5). February 2019, DOI: 10.5694/mja2.50004"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92124"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"626"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92124","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92124"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-25T19:11:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-25T19:11:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"626"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109727"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d